  "prompt": "What is a good substitute for chipotle powder?",
  "response": "If you're looking for a substitute for chipotle powder, you have several options that can provide a similar smoky heat:\n\n1. **Smoked Paprika**: This will give you the smoky flavor, though it lacks the heat that chipotle powder provides. You might want to add a touch of cayenne pepper to bring in some heat.\n\n2. **Ancho Chili Powder**: Made from dried and ground poblano peppers, ancho chili powder has a mild heat and a rich, slightly sweet flavor. It\u2019s less smoky but can work well in many dishes.\n\n3. **Cayenne Pepper with Smoked Paprika**: Combining these two can mimic both the heat and smokiness of chipotle powder. Adjust the ratio according to your taste preference.\n\n4. **Adobo Sauce**: If you happen to have canned chipotle peppers in adobo, you can use the sauce for both heat and smokiness. It's particularly good in recipes that can accommodate some added moisture.\n\n5. **Hot Sauce with Smoke**: Some hot sauces have a smoky flavor and can be used as a liquid substitute in recipes that allow for a bit of added liquid.\n\nRemember, each substitute may slightly change the flavor profile of your dish, so adjust quantities to taste.",
